05602nam a22008295i 9783110742480DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021952019  a9783110742480  a(DE-B1597)577190  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aREL0670802bisacsh00aKierkegaardian Essays :bA Festschrift in Honour of George Pattison /ced. by Clare Carlisle, Steven Shakespeare. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (XIV, 218 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aKierkegaard Studies. Monograph Series ,x1434-2952 ;v3100tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tTable of Contents -- tWhat Does It Mean to Be Human? -- tTeach Us to Care and Not to Care -- tSpeculate Like a Kierkegaardian! -- tThe Riddle of Irony -- tInterlude I: Wayward Intimacies -- tA Smile From Every Child -- t“Was It—Love?” “No, No, It Was Søren Kierkegaard” -- tThe Generous Eye -- tOn Love, Teaching, and Forgetting -- tInterlude II: Summon the Earnest Thought of Death -- tVocation and the Voice of Conscience -- tFrom the Lily and the Bird, Let us Learn: Nothing -- tMelancholy and Modernity -- tWhy Kierkegaard? Seventy Theses, Declarations, and Expressions of Thanks -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSøren Kierkegaard argued that the most essential truths come to light by asking "How…?" This innovative collection of essays by leading scholars focuses on this questioning "How?", asking how we should relate to ourselves, to others, and to God; how we should be in the world; how we can become human. The result is a searching, original colloquium on what it means to be Kierkegaardian in the 21st century.The adjective "Kierkegaardian" names many possibilities: ways of philosophizing, choosing, loving, looking, listening, reading, writing, teaching, making art, praying, going to church – or not going to church. "How" gestures to subjectivity, one of Kierkegaard’s most fundamental philosophical categories, while "What" signals an objectifying line of thought. The authors of these essays suggest that the crucial Kierkegaardian question is not what we are and ought to do, but how we can remain true to the finitude, passivity, and ambiguity of human existence.While this Kierkegaardian "how" is often acknowledged by scholars, it is rarely thematized directly. Attending to it elicits new kinds of argument and reflection. Kierkegaardian Essays proposes a fresh approach to Kierkegaard, and is essential reading for experts and students alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 4aExistentialismus. 4aKierkegaard. 4aPattison, George. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / History.2bisacsh  aKierkegaard.  aPattison, George.  aexistentialism.1 aBarnett, Christopher B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlisle, Clare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlisle, Clare, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDalferth, Ingolf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDamgaard, Iben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarff, Joakim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhawaja, Noreen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirkpatrick, Matthew D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarino, Gordon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMulhall, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPyper, Hugh S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRasmussen, Joel D. S., econt